{{十干十二支}} '''Wu''' (戊, bo, tsuchinoe) is the 5th of the {{ill|Heavenly Stems|lt=Ten Heavenly Stems|8=en|ja|十干}}. It is different from the character {{ill|戉|ja|戉}}.
== Overview == * In the {{ill|Yin-Yang and Five Elements theory|ja|陰陽五行説|1=Yin-Yang and Five Elements Theory}}, Wu is associated with the yang aspect of the element {{ill|Earth (element)|ja|土}}. In Japan, it is also called "{{ill|Tsuchinoe|ja|つちのえ}}" (Elder Brother of Earth). * In terms of direction, it corresponds to the {{ill|Center|ja|中央}}. Regarding time, it refers to around 4 a.m., with the period from 4 a.m. to 6 a.m. known as "{{ill|Boya|ja|戊夜}}." * The character "戊" is an {{ill|ideogram|ja|象形文字}} representing a weapon resembling a battle-axe.<ref>{{Citation| author=Ji Xusheng| year=2014| title=Shuowen Xinzheng| location=Taipei| publisher=Yiwen Press| isbn=978-957-520-168-5| pages=962–93}}</ref><ref>{{Citation| author=Ge Liang| year=2022| title=Rediscovery of Chinese Characters| location=Shanghai| publisher=Shanghai Calligraphy and Painting Press| isbn=978-7-5479-2884-4| pages=102–105}}</ref> Its use to denote the fifth of the Ten Heavenly Stems is a case of {{ill|Jiajie|ja|仮借}} (phonetic loan). * When used in ordinal contexts, Wu represents the 5th position. * Years ending with the digit 8 in the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|西暦}} are designated as Wu years. Another name for the Wu year is "{{ill|Zhuoyong|ja|著雍}}" (also written as "{{ill|著雝|ja|著雝}}").<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ancient Alternative Names and Explanations of Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches |url=https://www.cidianwang.com/shufazuopin/jiaocheng/932596.htm |website=www.cidianwang.com |access-date=2024-03-08}}</ref> * In {{ill|Chinese chemical nomenclature|ja|化合物命名法}}, it is used in the names of compounds containing five carbon atoms, such as {{ill|Pentane|ja|ペンタン}} and the {{ill|Pentyl group|ja|ペンチル基}}. * Its counterpart is {{ill|Gui|ja|癸}} (Mizunoto). * The {{ill|Lucky direction|ja|恵方}} associated with Wu is south-southeast, slightly south (165 degrees).
